    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Thanks. That's a good start, but the part about 'intent theory' being a criticism makes it sound like the idea of substantive due process is something people are constantly fighting against or questioning. Can you explain why the 'intent theory' is considered the more accurate way to read the Constitution, compared to the substantive due process approach?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The 'intent theory' or originalism posits that the Constitution should be interpreted reflecting what the framers originally intended. Substantive due process, on the other hand, allows courts to extend beyond text to protect rights they deduce to be foundational. Critics of substantive due process, including proponents of the intent theory, argue that it's the judiciary superseding the democratic process by drawing these rights out of the Constitution's text. They emphasize that it looks at the Constitution as a living, breathing document guiding citizens with its evolving social justice interpretations. According to them, the power of passing and amending laws should rest with representative democracy instead of inordinate reference to implied rights in the Constitution to quickly rectify inequities or issues raised by injustices. They put forth the idea that the framers wouldn't have intentionally included these protections in their 18th-century writings, hence the existence of those rights is constitutionally invalid. Intra-constitutionally, snapshots of the Constitution that contemporary scholars sometimes use to demonstrate that civil rights are in the Constitution would be considered civil rights as they are phrased and expressed within them, thus refuting any claims made. In short, the intent theory asserts that civil rights extend only as far as positive expressions written within the Constitution are",
      "source": "target",
